rdf:Description.dct:title: Human Reference Atlas Value Set
rdf:Description.dct:description: The value set for the Human Reference Atlas metadata records as part of the Human BioMolecular Atlas Program (HuBMAP) (https://hubmapconsortium.org)

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for analytes.
A long linear double-stranded polymer formed from nucleotides attached to a deoxyribose backbone and found in the nucleus of a cell; associated with the transmission of genetic information.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: DNA

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Single-stranded long chain of nucleotides containing ribose. It is the end product of DNA transcription by the enzyme RNA polymerase. It is essential in protein synthesis.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ribonucleic Acid

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A group of complex organic macromolecules composed of one or more chains (linear polymers) of alpha-L-amino acids linked by peptide bonds and ranging in size from a few thousand to over 1 million Daltons. Proteins are fundamental genetically encoded components of living cells with specific structures and functions dictated by amino acid sequence.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Protein

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A compound of two or more amino acids where the alpha carboxyl group of one is bound to the alpha amino group of another.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Peptide

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A class of hydrocarbon-containing organic compounds. Lipids are insoluble in water but soluble in nonpolar solvents and play important roles in living organisms: these roles include functioning as energy storage molecules, serving as structural components of cell membranes, and constituting important signaling molecules. Lipids can be subdivided into 2 groups: fatty acids and glycerides.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Lipid

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Any substance involved in metabolism, either as a product of metabolism or as necessary for metabolism.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Metabolite

rdf:Description.skos:definition: The genetic material of the nucleus, consisting of deoxyribonucleoprotein, which occurs in two forms during the phase between mitotic divisions: 1) as heterochromatin, seen as condensed, readily stainable clumps; 2) as euchromatin, dispersed lightly staining or nonstaining material. During mitotic division the chromatin condenses into chromosomes.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Chromatin

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A biomacromolecule consisting of large numbers of monosaccharide residues linked glycosidically. This term is commonly used only for those containing more than ten monosaccharide residues.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Polysaccharide

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A fluorescent dye used to stain biological specimens.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Fluorochrome

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Endogenous fluorescence originates from naturally occurring fluorescent compounds, including structural proteins (e.g., elastin and collagens), lipids, or cellular metabolic cofactors [e.g., nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) and flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD)]
The term used to refer to the carbohydrate portion of N-glycoproteins when attached to a nitrogen from asparagine or arginine side-chains.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: N-glycan

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms of microanatomic structure.
The smallest units of living structure capable of independent existence, composed of a membrane-enclosed mass of protoplasm and containing a nucleus or nucleoid.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Cell

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A body within the cell, surrounded by a membrane, within which lie the chromosomes, one or more nucleoli, combined with proteins, and exhibits mitosis.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nucleus

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for assay techniques.
A DNA sequencing assay that intends to provide information about the sequence of an entire genome of an organism.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Whole genome sequencing assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An ATAC-seq assay in which single nuclei are isolated from frozen tissue samples, through a protocol designed to maximally preserve nucleus integrity during sample processing and optimize transposase-mediated fragmentation of chromatin in individual nuclei.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Single-nucleus ATAC-seq

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A type of tandem mass spectrometry where isotopomer labels are employed for accurate quantification and identification of specific proteins.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Tandem mass tag mass spectrometry assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An autofluorescence assay in which the light that is naturally emitted by a sample is visualized via microscopy after excitation of the sample with light at a suitable wavelength.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Autofluorescence microscopy assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An RNA-seq assay in which the sample that is sequenced is derived from a collection of cells, such as a tissue sample or entire cell culture, and therefore provides results representative of the aggregate of sample cells.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Bulk RNA-seq assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A multiplexed fluorescent antibody imaging assay that involves an iterative staining, imaging and dye inactivation workflow for over 60 biomarkers on a single fixed tissue section.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Cell DIVE multiplexed imaging assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A multiplexed fluorescent antibody imaging assay that involves a highly multiplexed analysis of up to 40 proteins in a tissue using cyclic detection of DNA-indexed antibody panels.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Co-detection by indexing assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A fluorescence in-situ hybridization assay which involves multiplex in situ digital quantification of targeted RNA transcripts in fresh or frozen tissue providing an understanding of the spatial organization of different cell types.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Decoding amplified targeted transcripts with fluorescence in situ hybridization assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A cytometry time of flight assay in which molecules of interest on or in cells are imaged through a system in which samples are labeled with multiple different rare-earth tagged antibodies. The sample is then ablated with a laser and the labeled material is detected by cytometry time of flight mass spectrometry.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Imaging mass cytometry assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A mass spectrometry assay where a sample mixture is first separated by liquid chromatography before being converted into ions which are characterized by using mass spectrometry based on their mass-to-charge ratio and relative abundance.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Liquid chromatography mass spectrometry assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A fluorescence microscopy that involves capturing of photons emitted by fluorophores excited with a thin sheet of laser light in a sample only in a relatively narrow plane by a detection objective oriented perpendicularly to the light sheet and imaged onto a detection device such as a CCD camera.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Lightsheet fluorescence microscopy assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A mass spectrometry assay that involves collection of spatially resolved mass spectra of a sample during microscopy where a pulse laser is used to produce both ionisation and vaporization. The sample is held in a matrix (such as dihydrobenzoic acid) to protect it from direct laser illumination and to separate the sample molecules. The spectra are used to visualise the spatial distribution of biomolecules by their molecular masses.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Matrix assisted laser desorption ionization imaging mass spectrometry assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A mass spectrometry assay that analyzes organic and biological molecules on a substrate by desorption of an analyte into a solvent bridge formed between two capillaries and the analysis surface. One capillary supplies solvent to create and maintain the bridge, while the second capillary transports the dissolved analyte from the bridge to the mass spectrometer. A high voltage applied between the inlet of mass spectrometer and the primary capillary creates a self-aspirating nanospray.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Nanospray desorption electrospray ionization assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An assay for transposase-accessible chromatin that uses sequencing which involves single cell combinatorial indexing ('sci-') strategy where nucleic acids from each of many cells are uniquely tagged through several rounds of split-pool barcoding which enables identification of single cells without single cell isolation.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Single cell combinatorial indexing assay for transposase-accessessable chromatin using sequencing

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A single-cell RNA sequencing assay that involves single cell combinatorial indexing ('sci-') strategy to profile the transcriptomes of single cells or nuclei without single cell isolation.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Single-cell combinatorial indexing RNA sequencing assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A fluorescence in-situ hybridization assay that involves ultra-resolution imaging of cell activity by targetting thousands of single molecules with fluorescent probes which find and hybridize with complementary DNA or RNA sequences in the tissue sample, thus enabling identification of those molecules directly in single cells with their spatial context preserved.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Sequential fluorescence in-situ hybridization assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An RNA-seq assay that involves transfer of RNA from tissue sections onto a surface covered in DNA-barcoded beads with known positions, allowing the locations of the RNA to be inferred by sequencing.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Slide-seq assay

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for means of storing materials.
An indication that a material has been stored in liquid nitrogen.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Liquid nitrogen storage

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An indication that a material has been stored in liquid nitrogen vapor.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Liquid nitrogen vapor storage

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A sample that is shipped in a frozen state maintained with dry ice.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Frozen on dry ice

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A specimen that has been subjected to and adjusted to the average ambient temperature of a room, usually considered to be around 20 degrees C (68 degrees F).
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Specimen at room temperature

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for material entity that is created or changed during material processing.
is a collection of short paired tags from the two ends of DNA fragments are extracted and covalently linked as ditag constructs
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: paired-end library

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A cDNA library that is a collection of short tags from only one end of DNA fragments.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: single-end library

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for different machine settings.
This is a set of controlled terms for scan direction.
This is a set of controlled terms for tile configuration.
This is a set of controlled terms for different kinds of medium used in processing a sample material.
This is a set of controlled terms for different kinds of preparation medium.
A processed material that is a mixture of formalin (formaldehyde), phosphates, and water used as a standard fixative for diagnostic preparations.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Neutral buffered formalin

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Phosphate buffered saline (abbreviated PBS) is a buffer solution commonly used in biochemistry. It is a salty solution containing sodium chloride, sodium phosphate and in some preparations potassium chloride and potassium phosphate. The buffer helps to maintain a constant pH. The concentration usually matches the human body (isotonic).
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Phosphate buffered saline solution

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Trade name for an aqueous, non-toxic tissue storage reagent that rapidly permeates tissues to stabilize and protect cellular RNA.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: RNALater

rdf:Description.skos:definition: The primary alcohol that is the simplest aliphatic alcohol, comprising a methyl and an alcohol group.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Methanol

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A primary alcohol that is ethane in which one of the hydrogens is substituted by a hydroxy group.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ethanol

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A proprietary system comprised of a formalin-free tissue fixative and stabilizing reagent designed to preserve tissue structures without damaging biomolecules. This allows both histologic examination and isolation of RNA, miRNA, DNA, and/or proteins from a single sample.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: PAXgene tissue system

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for different kinds of storage medium.
A solution of water soluble glycols and resins that provide a specimen support matrix for cryostat sectioning at temperatures of -10 degrees C and below.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Optimal cutting temperature compound

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Refers to a process where a sample is preserved with formalin and then embedded into a paraffin block for sectioning.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Formalin-fixed paraffin-embedded

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for different kinds of chemical solution used in processing sample materials.
This is a set of controlled terms for different kinds of perfusion solution.
This is a set of controlled terms for different kinds of transport solution.
A sodium bicarbonate-buffered medium formulated for use in a 5-10% carbon dioxide atmosphere. It is used in the cell culture of human lymphoid cells.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Roswell Park Memorial Institute 1640 Medium

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A serum-free medium for supporting the growth of adherent mammalian cells. It contains a combination of 6 salts, 13 essential amino acids, and 8 vitamins and is intended for use in a humidified incubator where the air contains 5% carbon dioxide.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Dulbecco's Modified Eagle Medium

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for techniques used in the laboratory for scientific research.
This is a set of controlled terms for techniques used to analyze and study different aspects of samples.
An analytical technique wherein ions are separated according to their ratio of charge to mass. From the mass spectrum produced, the atomic weight of the particle can be deduced.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Mass Spectrometry

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Any technology or method that aids in the visualization of any biological process, cell, tissue or organ for use in screening, diagnosis, surgical procedures or therapy.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Imaging Technique

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A technique in which mass spectra are acquired in a spatially resolved manner. This is typically achieved by scanning a laser or primary ion beam over a sample and acquiring a mass spectrum at each position.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Mass Spectrometry Imaging

rdf:Description.skos:definition: The process of determining the sequence of amino acids within a protein molecule.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Protein Sequencing

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for techniques used in sample staining.
Determination of a value is not relevant in the current context.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Not applicable

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Not known, observed, recorded; or reported as unknown by the data contributor.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Unknown

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A major division of the nervous system that contains nerves which connect the central nervous system (CNS) with sensory organs, other organs, muscles, blood vessels and glands.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Peripheral nervous system

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Any of the rounded masses of lymphoid tissue that are surrounded by a capsule of connective tissue, are distributed along the lymphatic vessels, and contain numerous lymphocytes which filter the flow of lymph.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Lymph node

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Muscular duct that propels urine from the kidneys to the urinary bladder, or related organs.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ureter

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A subdivision of the digestive tract that connects the small intestine to the cloaca or anus.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Large intestine

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Taxon notes:" the ascidian tube-like heart lacks chambers....The ascidian heart is formed after metamorphosis as a simple tube-like structure with a single-layered myoepithelium that is continuous with a single-layered pericar- dial wall. It lacks chambers and endocardium.... The innovation of the chambered heart was a key event in vertebrate evolution, because the chambered heart generates one-way blood flow with high pressure, a critical requirement for the efficient blood supply of large-body vertebrates... all extant vertebrates have hearts with two or more chambers (Moorman and Christoffels 2003)" DOI:10.1101/gad.1485706 A myogenic muscular circulatory organ found in the vertebrate cardiovascular system composed of chambers of cardiac muscle. It is the primary circulatory organ.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Heart

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An organ that detects light.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Eye

rdf:Description.skos:definition: The gonad of a female organism which contains germ cells.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ovary

rdf:Description.skos:definition: The female muscular organ of gestation in which the developing embryo or fetus is nourished until birth.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Uterus

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Distensible musculomembranous organ situated in the anterior part of the pelvic cavity in which urine collects before excretion.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Urinary bladder

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An endoderm derived structure that produces precursors of digestive enzymes and blood glucose regulating hormones.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Pancreas

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A segment of the hindlimb that corresponds to the joint connecting a hindlimb stylopod and zeugopod.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Knee

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Organ of metabolic interchange between fetus and mother, partly of embryonic origin and partly of maternal origin.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Placenta

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Respiration organ that develops as an outpocketing of the esophagus.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Lung

rdf:Description.skos:definition: The organ covering the body that consists of the dermis and epidermis.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Skin of body

rdf:Description.skos:definition: The organ that functions to filter blood and to store red corpuscles and platelets.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Spleen

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An exocrine gland which secretes bile and functions in metabolism of protein and carbohydrate and fat, synthesizes substances involved in the clotting of the blood, synthesizes vitamin A, detoxifies poisonous substances, stores glycogen, and breaks down worn-out erythrocytes.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Liver

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Subdivision of digestive tract that connects the stomach to the large intestine and is where much of the digestion and absorption of food takes place (with the exception of ruminants).
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Small intestine

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A paired organ of the urinary tract which has the production of urine as its primary function.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Kidney

rdf:Description.skos:definition: The prostate gland is a partly muscular, partly glandular body that is situated near the base of the mammalian male urethra and secretes an alkaline viscid fluid which is a major constituent of the ejaculatory fluid.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Prostate gland

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Anatomical structure of largely lymphoid tissue that functions in cell-mediated immunity by being the site where T cells develop.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Thymus

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A network of blunt ended vessels lacking direct connection to the blood vascular system. These vessels collect and drain fluids and macromolecules from interstitial spaces throughout the animal. They derive from a subpopulation of endothelial cells and have walls that are much thinner than the blood carrying vessels. Lymphatic vessels are usually classified as either superficial or deep.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Lymph vasculature

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A kidney that is part of a left side of organism
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Left kidney

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A kidney that is part of a right side of organism.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Right kidney

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An eye that is part of a left side of organism.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Left eye

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An eye that is part of a right side of organism.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Right eye

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for defining and rendering a concept unique.
This is a set of controlled terms for defining a condition.
Having no significant health-related issues.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Healthy

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An indication that an anatomic structure has detectable aberrations.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Diseased

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for defining an organ laterality.
Being or located on or directed toward the side of the body to the east when facing north.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Right

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Being or located on or directed toward the side of the body to the west when facing north.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Left

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A medial line, especially the medial line or medial plane of the body (or some part of the body).
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Midline

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for defining an assessment answer.
No person or thing, nobody, not any.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: None

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for defining an attribute or a property.
Created, done, or existing within a company or organization.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: In-House

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for stain types.

Hematoxylin is a dark purplish dye that stains the chromatin (nuclear material) within the nucleus. Eosin is an orangish-pink to red dye that stains the cytoplasmic material including connective tissue and collagen.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Hematoxylin and eosin stain

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An alcohol soluble copper phthalocyanine dye, and cresyl violet, an organic compound that is commonly used as a counter stain, to determine the presence of myelin as well as helicobacter and campylobacter bacterial species.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Luxol fast blue/Cresyl violet stain

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is an all-round useful stain for many things, including glycogen, mucin, mucoprotein, glycoprotein, as well as fungi. The reaction is based on the oxidation of glycol group to aldehydes by periodate. The schiff's reagent selectively stains the aldehydes to a rose pink color. PAS is useful for outlining tissue structures--basement membranes, capsules, blood vessels, etc.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Periodic acid-Schiff stain

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Acid dyes and washes to selectively dye the structural elements in tissue samples in three or more contrasting colors.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Trichrome stain

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for measurement units.
This is a set of controlled terms for area unit.
An area unit which is equal to one ten thousandth of a square meter or 10^[-4] m^[2].
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: square centimeter

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An area unit which is equal to one millionth of a square meter or 10^[-6] m^[2].
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: square millimeter

rdf:Description.skos:definition: An area unit which is equal to an area enclosed by a square with sides each 1 micrometer long.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: square micrometer

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for length unit.
A length unit which is equal to one hundredth of a meter or 10^[-2] m.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: centimeter

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A length unit which is equal to one thousandth of a meter or 10^[-3] m.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: millimeter

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A length unit which is equal to one millionth of a meter or 10^[-6] m.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: micrometer

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A length unit which is equal to one thousandth of one millionth of a meter or 10^[-9] m.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: nanometer

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for volume unit.
A volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a cubic meter or 10^[-9] m^[3], or to 1 ml.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: cubic centimeter

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for liquid volume unit.
A volume unit which is equal to one thousandth of a cubic meter or 10^[-3] m^[3], or to 1 decimeter.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: liter

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A volume unit which is equal to one thousandth of a liter or 10^[-3] L, or to 1 cubic centimeter.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: milliliter

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A volume unit which is equal to one millionth of a liter or 10^[-6] L.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: microliter

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for weight unit.
A mass unit which is equal to the mass of the International Prototype Kilogram kept by the BIPM at Svres, France.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: kilogram

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A mass unit which is equal to one thousandth of a kilogram or 10^[-3] kg.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: gram

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A mass unit which is equal to one thousandth of a gram or 10^[-3] g.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: milligram

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A mass unit which is equal to one millionth of a gram or 10^[-6] g.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: microgram

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A mass unit which is equal to one thousandth of one millionth of a gram or 10^[-9] g.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: nanogram

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for time unit.
A time unit which is equal to 60 seconds.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: minute

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A time unit which is equal to 3600 seconds or 60 minutes.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: hour

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A time unit which is equal to 24 hours.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: day

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A time unit which is approximately equal to the length of time of one of cycle of the moon's phases which in science is taken to be equal to 30 days.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: month

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A time unit which is equal to 12 months which in science is taken to be equal to 365.25 days.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: year

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for mass density
A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in milligrams divided by the volume in milliliters.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: milligram per milliliter

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in micrograms divided by the volume in millliters.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: microgram per milliliter

rdf:Description.skos:definition: A mass unit density which is equal to mass of an object in nanograms divided by the volume in microliters.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: nanogram per microliter

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for the scientific instrument vendors.
This is a set of controlled terms for the acquisition instrument vendors.
Provides development and manufacture of high performance scientific digital cameras, microscopy systems and spectrographs for academic, industrial and government applications.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Andor

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Bruker Daltonics is subsidary of Bruker Corporation American. Bruker is manufacturer of scientific instruments for molecular and materials research, as well as for industrial and applied analysis.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Bruker Daltonics

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Cytiva is the new name of the former GE Healthcare Life Sciences biopharma business following its acquisition by Danaher Corporation, according to an April 1, 2020 announcement. Provider of life sciences brands such as KTA, Amersham, HyClone, MabSelect and Whatman.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Cytiva

rdf:Description.skos:definition: American company incorporated that develops, manufactures and markets integrated systems for the analysis of genetic variation and biological function. Provides a line of products and services that serve the sequencing, genotyping and gene expression and proteomics markets. Its headquarters are located in San Diego, California.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Illumina

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Pioneer in high definition spatial proteomics, tissue imaging and analysis to accelerate medical discovery and improve human health. With MIBI technology and expertise of pathology and data science teams, Ionpath provides actionable insights to translational and clinical researchers at leading pharmaceutical, biotechnology, and research organizations in immuno-oncology, immunology, neuroscience, and infectious disease research.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ionpath

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Direct sales organization that develops and manufactures automation sensors, vision systems, barcode readers, laser markers, measuring instruments, and digital microscopes. Founder Takemitsu Takizaki. Headquarters Osaka, Osaka, Japan.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Keyence

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Medical devices company that develops and supplies clinical diagnostics to pathology market. It is also research, instrument, and medical device company as well as division of Danaher Corporation with headquarters Wetzlar, Germany.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Leica Biosystems

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Manufacturer of mass spectrometry instrumentation used in biomedical and environmental applications. Originally started by scientists from the University of Toronto Institute for Aerospace Studies, it is now part of Danaher Corporation with the SCIEX R&D division still located in Toronto, Canada.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Sciex

rdf:Description.skos:definition: American company engaged in design, manufacture and sale of biological research equipment based on integrated fluidic circuit technology. Founders leveraged their semiconductor experience to create integrated circuits that carried fluids rather than electrons.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Standard BioTools

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Commercial vendor and service provider of laboratory reagents and antibodies. Supplier of scientific instrumentation, reagents and consumables, and software services.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Thermo Fisher Scientific

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Manufacturer of light, electron, X-ray and ion microscope systems. Offers solutions for correlative microscopy. Provides products and services for life sciences, materials and industrial research, as well as education and clinical practice.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Zeiss Microscopy

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Manufacturer of optical sensors including, photomultiplier tubes, electric light sources, and other optical devices and their applied instruments for scientific, technical and medical use.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Hamamatsu Photonics

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for the preparation instrument vendors.
American biotechnology company that designs and manufactures gene sequencing technology used in scientific research.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: 10x Genomics

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Company offers sample preparation solutions for Mass Spectrometry Imaging. HTX delivers customized solutions for sample preparation and workflow automation of advanced analytical platforms.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: HTX Technologies

rdf:Description.skos:definition: This is a set of controlled terms for the instrument models.

Bernd Bodenmiller is a quantitative biologist who develops novel experimental and computational approaches for the quantitative analysis of tumor ecosystems to improve our understanding of the mechanisms of tumor development for the benefit of patients. He is the founding director of the Department of Quantitative Biomedicine (DQBM) at the University of Zurich, which fosters research and education at the interface of biomedical research, biotechnology, and computational biology to guide development of next-generation precision medicine. Prof. Bodenmiller obtained his PhD at ETH Zrich and he performed his postdoctoral training at Stanford University. In 2013 he became SNF/ERC Assistant Professor at the University of Zurich. In 2020 he was appointed as Dual Professor for Quantitative Biomedicine at the UZH and at ETH Zurich. His group pioneered the development of imaging mass cytometry, an approach that enables simultaneously imaging of over 40 proteins and transcripts in tumor tissues as well as many computational tools for spatial tissue analysis. His groups applies these methods to unravel how cells in the tumor ecosystem drive cancer development to identify mechanisms that might be exploited for therapeutic targeting.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Bernd Bodenmiller

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Clive Wasserfall trained in clinical laboratory medicine in South Africa prior to pursuing a MS in clinical chemistry at the University of Florida and a PhD in immunology at the Technical University of Dresden. Located at the University of Florida in the USA my laboratory focus is on the immunopathogenesis of Type 1 Diabetes (T1D).
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Clive Wasserfall

rdf:Description.skos:definition: Dr. Nolan is the Rachford and Carlota A. Harris Professor in the Department of Pathology at Stanford University School of Medicine. He trained with Leonard Herzenberg (for his Ph.D.) and Nobelist Dr. David Baltimore (for postdoctoral work for the first cloning/characterization of NF-B p65/RelA and the development of rapid retroviral production systems). He has published over 300 research papers, is the holder of 40US patents, and has been honored as one of the top 25 inventors at Stanford University. Dr. Nolan is the first recipient of the Teal Innovator Award (2012) from the Department of Defense (a $3.3 million grant for advanced studies in ovarian cancer), the first recipient of an FDA BAAA to an academic institution ($3 million for Bio-agent protection grant from the FDA for a Cross-Species Immune System Reference), received the award for Outstanding Research Achievement in 2011 from the Nature Publishing Group for his development of CyTOF applications in the immune system, Elected as a Fellows of the American Institute for Medical and Biological Engineering, and is the recipient of the Ernest Cotlove Award from the Academy of Clinical Laboratory Physicians & Scientists. Dr. Nolan is an outspoken proponent of translating public & private investment in basic research to serve the public welfare. Dr. Nolan was the founder of Rigel Inc. (NASDAQ: RIGL), and Nodality, Inc., a diagnostics development company and serves on the Boards of Directors of several companies, as well as consults for other biotechnology companies. DVS Sciences, on which he is Chair of the Scientific Advisory Board, was recently sold (link) underscoring the considerable interest in the technology in academic and clinical venues. He was the co-Founder of BINA, a sequence analysis company sold to Roche, and is the co-Founder of Apprise, Akoya, and IonPathall companies in the single cell analysis or pathology imaging arena. The latter 3 companies are either venture funded or recently acquired. Dr. Nolans areas of research include hematopoiesis, cancer and leukemia, autoimmunity and inflammation, and computational approaches for network and systems immunology. His most recent efforts are focused on a single cell analysis advance using a mass spectrometry-flow cytometry hybrid device, the so-call CyTOF. The approach uses an advanced ion plasma source to determine the levels of tagged reagents bound to cellsenabling a vast increase in the number of parameters that can be measured per cell. Another recent innovation is termed molecular ion beam imaging (MIBI) a system that also uses mass tags that will enable sub-light imaging (50 nm resolution) of tissue sections as well as the CODEX system enabling 50 or more parameters per image. Dr. Nolans efforts are to enable a deeper understanding not only of normal immune function, trauma, and other inflammatory events but also detailed substructures of leukemias and solid cancerswhich will enable wholly new understandings that will enable better management of disease and clinical outcomes.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Garry Nolan
